---
import rawDashboard from "../data/dashboard.json";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import type { Dashboard } from "../types";

const dashboard = rawDashboard as unknown as Dashboard;
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Methodology and limitations | MarkSignal AU" description="How MarkSignal selects, resolves, compares, and describes Australian trade mark filings.">
  <section class="page-hero method-hero">
    <div><p class="eyebrow"><span></span> Reproducible by design</p><h1>Methodology<br /><em>before inference.</em></h1><p>Every surfaced reason is deterministic, versioned, and recoverable from a minimised evidence record.</p></div>
    <div class="method-index"><span>On this page</span><a href="#source">01 Source</a><a href="#entity-resolution">02 Resolution</a><a href="#signals-method">03 Signals</a><a href="#limitations">04 Limits</a><a href="#demonstration-data">05 Demo data</a></div>
  </section>

  <article class="prose-layout">
    <aside><p>Current model</p><strong>1.0.0</strong><span>4 reasons<br />90 maximum points<br />0 hidden weights</span></aside>
    <div class="prose">
      <section id="source"><p class="section-number">01</p><h2>Source and selection</h2><p>MarkSignal uses IP RAPID, IP Australia's weekly public relational dataset. The production adapter reads the documented application, party-activity, description, classification, event, and link table headers. It joins tables only through the documented pair of IP right type and application number.</p><p>The first pass streams current organisation applicant rows and matches them against curated YAML aliases. Later passes retain only those application numbers. Addresses, postcodes, contact details, agents, opponents, and private-person applicant records are not published.</p><div class="method-note"><strong>Source fact</strong><span>Application status, dates, descriptions, Nice classes, and standing event history come from selected public records.</span></div></section>
      <section id="entity-resolution"><p class="section-number">02</p><h2>Applicant entity resolution</h2><p>Names are normalised for Unicode, punctuation, whitespace, ampersands, and a narrow set of legal-form variants such as Proprietary Limited and Pty Ltd. Legal suffixes are retained. The resulting value must exactly match an alias declared in a version-controlled watchlist.</p><p>Character similarity can suggest a review candidate, but it cannot merge organisations. An alias collision fails validation. A filing that matches more than one watched organisation is skipped for manual review rather than assigned arbitrarily.</p></section>
      <section id="signals-method"><p class="section-number">03</p><h2>Signal calculations</h2><div class="formula-list"><div><span>+25</span><strong>New class</strong><p>One or more current Nice classes have not appeared in an earlier selected filing for the resolved applicant.</p></div><div><span>+25</span><strong>Filing cluster</strong><p>At least three marks for the same resolved applicant fall within seven days and exceed a 0.62 character-trigram cosine similarity threshold.</p></div><div><span>+20</span><strong>Long filing gap</strong><p>The filing follows the applicant's previous selected dated filing by at least 365 days.</p></div><div><span>+20</span><strong>Novel tokens</strong><p>Meaningful words in the mark have not appeared in an earlier selected mark for that applicant. A short published stop-word list is excluded.</p></div></div><p>The points are a transparent ordering device. They are not trained, probabilistic, or predictive. A higher score means more configured conditions were met, not that a launch or other commercial event is more likely.</p></section>
      <section id="limitations"><p class="section-number">04</p><h2>Limitations</h2><ul><li>Watchlists are curated and incomplete. Subsidiaries, former names, and filing agents may create gaps.</li><li>IP RAPID is weekly, so the dashboard is not a real-time registry view.</li><li>Application date can differ from the earliest filing or priority date, particularly for international rights.</li><li>Current classes do not describe every detail of the goods and services claim.</li><li>Text similarity reports related wording only. It does not establish ownership, copying, confusion, or infringement.</li><li>A status or event reflects the published administrative record and can later be corrected.</li><li>Absence from MarkSignal does not mean an organisation made no filing.</li></ul><div class="method-warning"><strong>A filing is not a launch announcement.</strong><p>{dashboard.disclaimer}</p></div></section>
      <section id="demonstration-data"><p class="section-number">05</p><h2>Demonstration data</h2><p>The repository includes a complete synthetic dataset so the static application, downloads, tests, and evidence paths can be evaluated before processing the large official archive. Fictional names prevent demonstration scores from being mistaken for real corporate findings.</p><p>Production builds set <code>is_demo</code> to false, provide official Australian Trade Mark Search links, and preserve the IP RAPID retrieval manifest. The interface labels the current mode prominently.</p><a class="button button--primary" href={`${base}data/`}>Inspect generated data →</a></section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
